T1  - The risk of multiple sclerosis among German World War II refugees: A contribution from the epidemiological area of South Hesse, West Germany.
T2  - Das Multiple-Skleorose-Risiko unter den Heimatvertriebenen. Ein Beitrag aus dem epidemiologischen Areal Sudhessens.
A1  - Lauer, K
A1  - Firnhaber, W

Y1  - 1986//
N2  - Discusses etiological factors in the incidence of multiple sclerosis (MS) and the hypothesis that ethnic minorities or groups of individuals subjected to shared traumatic and/or stressful experiences may share a greater vulnerability to the disease. The authors surveyed the incidence of MS among World War II refugees from previously-German Eastern territories who had settled in southern Hesse in West Germany, using the local population as controls. Survey data show no measurable difference in MS incidence between Ss and controls, with the minor exception of a higher number of East Prussians among the German war refugees who did suffer from the disease. It is hypothesized that shared etiological factors among members of that group might be genetic and environmental rather than connected with their displaced person status. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
