T1  - When young children move..
A1  - Jalongo, Mary R

Y1  - 1985//
N2  - Relocation has been identified as a disruptive element in children's lives because of the unusual demands that it places on children's adaptive responses. Four vignettes illustrate how children cope with emotional, social, and environmental changes in fairly predictable ways and show how moving can cause such reactions as fear of parental abandonment, depression, and anger. To help children adjust to moving, parents should keep them informed and involved, emphasize similarities between the old and new environments, be alert to verbal and nonverbal expressions of feelings, promote peer interaction, and use children's literature to show how others cope with moving. A list is appended of 14 children's books about moving. (29 ref) (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
