T1  - The mental health of immigrants: A reassessment of concepts.
A1  - Salvendy, John T

Y1  - 1983//
N2  - Reviews past and present views on links between immigration and mental illness. A prevailing major assumption has been that the process of immigration itself is so traumatic that it increases the likelihood of mental disorder. Early monofactorial hypotheses suggested that a higher rate of mental illness in immigrants was due to natural negative selection or that the immigrant's usual psychological defenses were rendered useless in a new environment. More contemporary views recognize that a number of factors may affect the mental health of immigrants. These factors may include the sociocultural gap between the society of origin and the host country, change in SES, preparation prior to immigration, mastery of the new language, and the existence of a large local ethnic community. The effects of these factors on the immigration of the family, the single young adult, the elderly, and refugees are discussed. (47 ref) (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
