T1  - The inpatient treatment of adolescents in a milieu including younger children.
A1  - Olds, Jacqueline

Y1  - 1982//
N2  - Proposes a hospital environment in which disturbed adolescents and latency-aged children are included in the same setting, noting that many disturbed adolescents have failed to develop the necessary observing ego and displacement defenses against drives that latency-aged children learn through the constructive use of play. In this sort of mixed setting, it is useful to employ methods of play therapy without humiliating the adolescent with the use of actual toys. The adolescent's feelings of displacement can be learned through projective, nonthreatening tools such as stories and games, encouragement of task mastery, and the study of sibling relationships with younger children. The goal of this mixed hospital environment is to provide a structure in which the adolescent feels in control of his/her emotions with clear limits regarding what behavior is acceptable and what is not, since disturbed adolescents often have meager internal controls. Problems may arise when adolescents envy displays of affection (e.g., goodnight hugs) to younger children by staff, although such behavior may not be appropriate to their age level and often duplicates the situation in the adolescent's family that led to hospitalization. Staff can respond by involving adolescents in childcare and role modeling, providing new routes for their regressive feelings. (6 ref) (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
