T1  - Migrant children or the impossible identity.
T2  - Les enfants de migrants ou l'impossible identite.
A1  - Moussaoui, D
A1  - Sayeh, A

Y1  - 1982//
N2  - As Maghrebian families emigrate to France, their family relationships change drastically due to (1) a new cultural environment; (2) unrealistic goals; (3) the low job status of the father; (4) the mother's employment and her learning of French; and (5) the children's acculturation in nontraditional ways. A review of 265 medical records from 1974 through 1977 of Maghreb children at a hospital in Paris shows a difference between male and female behavior. Girls revolted against the family and often attempted suicide because their parents would not let them go out to dance or drink wine. Girls often teamed up with their mothers or a social worker against the father, with stormy results. Boys tended to turn against the host society by rebelling in school, engaging in mindless drunkenness and drug use, or becoming delinquents. At the age of 18 yrs, citizenship must be chosen. When these young adults choose French citizenship, their parents often view their choice as treasonous. However, these same young people would be unable to reinsert themselves successfully in Maghrebian society. (13 ref) (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
