T1  - From identity loss to invalidism among immigrant workers.
T2  - De la perte d'identite a l'invalidation chez le travailleur immigre.
A1  - Scotto, J.-C
A1  - Luccioni, H
A1  - Liauzu, J. P
A1  - Pin, M
A1  - Trouve, J. N

Y1  - 1982//
N2  - Immigrant mental pathology usually manifests itself in 2 ways: sudden acute delirium, mostly among the young, and hypochondriacal depression among mature persons. The prognosis for the former is good, but the latter often become invalids. A problem may be brought on by the issuance of identity papers, when an Algerian man, for instance, learns that he has dual nationality, without first having had a chance to adjust to this idea. Secondly, the acculturation process causes a Maghrebian to be torn between 2 cultures. A 3rd problem centers on the impact of the French environment on family structure, the reduced status of the father, and the now-ambiguous role of the mother. For the father, the change instills a belief that his body is useful only for work and biological functions. Any contracted illness then evolves easily into invalidism. (12 ref) (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
