T1  - The Maghrebian and his family from emigrant to immigrant status facing change and illness.
T2  - L'emigre-immigre maghrebin et sa famille face au changement et a la maladie.
A1  - Ammar, Sleim

Y1  - 1982//
N2  - North African migrations to France create 2 problems: those dealing with the integration of the immigrant into a new environment and those dealing with the reception given by the host society. This transition gives rise to numerous phantasms in immigrants, characterized as ambiguous and ambivalent, and involving both presence in the host country and absence from the country of origin. Anxiety and culpability are always present, impacting on conjugal stability, particularly when the wife remains isolated. Often, children see their fathers only on holidays, and they are subjected to cultural changes with new and different values, that may cause disease and accidents among family members and exacerbate physician-patient relations, particularly on the psychotherapeutic level. Bureaucratic complications between the governments of the 2 countries may cause the individuals to suffer more. To ameliorate this situation, physicians in both countries must cooperate in the treatment of psychosomatic and physiological disorders in emigrants and immigrants. (18 ref) (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
