T1  - Family history and schizophrenia: Characteristics of groups with and without positive family histories.
A1  - Shur, Eric

Y1  - 1982//
N2  - Examined social and demographic characteristics retrospectively in 475 hospitalized schizophrenics to test the hypothesis that they can be meaningfully distinguished by the presence or absence of psychiatric disorders in their relatives. Cases with a positive family history of psychiatric disorders (FHP cases) were significantly more likely to have been born in the UK and to have had older mothers (over 40 yrs of age). Those who had relatives with psychiatric disorders other than schizophrenia were significantly more likely to have been diagnosed as schizoaffective. Findings reflect a constitutional trait in parents of FHP cases that leads to delayed childbearing. The environmental stress theory of immigrant psychosis and the hypothesized genetic link between schizoaffective and affective disorders are supported. (16 ref) (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
