T1  - Psychoanalyses of children of survivors from the Nazi persecution: The continuing struggle of survivor parents.
A1  - Kestenberg, Judith S
A1  - Kestenberg, Milton

Y1  - 1980//
N2  - Describes the plight of the Jews persecuted by Nazis, stressing the loss of faith children experienced when they saw their parents degraded. The Nazi's assault on trust in the normal holding environment had the effect of a cumulative trauma even on those who were not subjected to the tortures and indignities of camps and ghettos. The fact that the Nazis condemned Jews as bad without possibility of redemption distinguishes them from all other victims. The few who were liberated carried with them the image of the world persecuting them. In turn, many host countries were suspicious of the newcomers. Survivors, in their effort to rehabilitate themselves, were impeded by the continuation of persecution inherent in the Nazi restitution practices. In addition, renewed attacks on Jews and on Israel and, most of all, the killing of Jewish children by terrorists were instrumental in the continued lack of trust on the part of the survivors. The task their children have set for themselves is to restore the image of their parents and regain trust in humanity. (13 ref) (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
