T1  - Briquet's Treatise on Hysteria: A synopsis and commentary.
T3  - A.M.A. Archives of General Psychiatry, JAMA Psychiatry
A1  - Mai, Francois M
A1  - Merskey, Harold

Y1  - 1980//
N2  - P. Briquet's Treatise on Hysteria, published in 1859, consists of a clinical and epidemiologic study of 430 patients seen over a 10-yr period. The etiologic factors were youth, female sex, "affective" and "impressionable" temperament, family history of the disorder, low social class, migration, sexual licentiousness, situational difficulties, and poor physical health. Briquet considered the "affective part of the brain" the final common pathway that mediated these causative agents. In treatment, he emphasized the importance of an improvement in social circumstances and the need to minimize environmental problems. It is concluded that the clinical and investigative approach of Briquet has an enduring relevance in the context of modern concepts of hysteria. (14 ref) (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
