T1  - Uprootment and anxiety.
A1  - Mostwin, Danuta

Y1  - 1976//
N2  - Discusses uprooting as a possible source of anxiety among Polish immigrants to the US who in many cases fail to communicate properly with their environment. Their feelings toward the mother country are intense and they feel guilty for not doing anything for her. Conflict of loyalties also disrupts their mental health. Consciously, they have developed a commitment to their mother country as well. The conflict may emerge when the balance between the loyalties is disturbed by some outside influence. Conflicts in the areas of employment, work satisfaction, current social status, etc, may lead to frustration and tension. The act of uprooting begins a long chain of crises, of which one is the emergence of a "third value," a new cultural identity that is neither with the country of origin nor with the receiving country, which is incorporated by the first generation's children as they identify with their parental models. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
