T1  - Mental hygiene in diminishing population areas.
A1  - Matsubara, Taro

Y1  - 1976//
N2  - Discusses mental health problems arising in Japan from the explosive population growth of industrial sections and the diminishing population in rural mountain areas of isolated villages. Young people are seeking their fortune in the cities where, in the new environment, they often develop schizophrenia. Families find adaptation to crowded, noisy, unfamiliar surroundings difficult. Old people may return to their native villages, where community life has meanwhile disintegrated; living alone, they develop alcoholism and senile dementia and often try to commit suicide. Statistics are cited to show the correlation between diminishing population and mental illness. A number of suggestions are offered for helping the newcomers to the cities, both young and old, and for taking care of old people who remain in their villages or return to them. The areas themselves should be encouraged to develop towns and industries. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
