T1  - The healer, the community or the bureaucrat.
A1  - Jaffe, Dennis T

Y1  - 1974//
N2  - Distinguishes 3 therapeutic methods (which partially overlap): (a) the bureaucratic approach, dominant in mental hospitals and other institutions, which isolates patients from staff and tries to compel them to behave properly; (b) the healer or guru approach, which tries to effect change through the personality of a leader (who need not be an agent of society); and (c) the community approach, which uses the patient's environment, an atmosphere in which he is free to talk to friends, to effect change. Personal experiences in working simultaneously at a halfway house with a supportive environment for residents and at an inpatient unit of a mental health center run on the bureaucratic model indicate the superiority of the former. Experience at a service agency for migrant young people where the boundary between staff and client was almost nonexistent validated the theory that participation in the governance of a community is itself therapeutic. However, bureaucratic therapy receives almost all of the financial and moral resources available. As for the healer-guru model, the danger is that the leader may assume an increasingly authoritarian role. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
