T1  - The social aetiology of schizophrenia in immigrant groups.
A1  - Bagley, Christopher

Y1  - 1971//
N2  - Reports evidence from a study of 2,089 cases of mental illness in a London borough that showed a higher rate of schizophrenia among ethnic minorities than among the major population. To identify specific social conditions predisposing one to schizophrenia, a sample of 27 schizophrenic West Indians was compared to like numbers of nonschizophrenic West Indians and English schizophrenics. The 3 groups did not differ in the number of life crises prior to illness onset. Both West Indian groups reported greater environmental stress than the English group. West Indian schizophrenics were significantly different from the other 2 groups in their higher occupational aspirations. In a society which blocks occupational ascendance to the nonwhite, high status-striving may be a social factor contributing to mental illness. (29 ref.) (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
