T1  - Family and peer relationships in children with paranoid delusions.
A1  - Arthur, Bettie
A1  - Schumann, Susanne

Y1  - 1970//
N2  - Studied 13 8.11-13.9 yr. old psychotic boys with average, or above, intelligence, whose symptomatology was highly similar to paranoid schizophrenia in adults, and whose delusions were not transient. Their interpersonal relationships are described, and an attempt is made to relate their family environment to their paranoid adjustment and fantastic elaboration of primitive fears and wishes. Each S grew up with parents who related to each other and to their sons primarily on a part-object basis. Each parent used the son to fulfill unconscious needs of his own. The mother emphasized the ideational side, the father the affective and impulsive components, and in failing to represent reality, both set the stage for an early split in S's personality. S thus failed to separate and individuate, promulgating the continuation of his narcissism. In summary, the study indicates that the child who is to become a paranoid schizophrenic is one who, without evidence of biologic abnormalities, will have had a pattern of disturbed development from infancy onward. (33 ref.) (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
