T1  - Changing society and mental health in eastern Africa.
A1  - Assael, M
A1  - German, G. A

Y1  - 1970//
N2  - Discusses the effects of social change and disintegration on the mental health of africans in uganda. 3 patient groups were studied: (a) ss admitted to a mental hospital between january and june 1968; (b) ss in a rural community, particularly those who are immigrants and those living alone; and (c) undergraduates referred to a psychiatrist because of conspicuous psychiatric morbidity. A much higher hospitalization rate was found for immigrants than for local people. Reasons for this are discussed, and are further illuminated by the rural community study which indicates that immigrants tend to live alone more often than locals, hold the poorest jobs, are least well fed, and are most afflicted by disease. Amongst the student ss, considered to be in the forefront of social change, the prevalence of conspicuous psychiatric morbidity seems to be no greater than in students at british universities. This might suggest that in the absence of factors, E.g., poverty, disease, and loneliness, social change per se has little decisive influence on mental health. Finally certain aspects of clinical problems are discussed, in particular the frequent occurrence of psychoses of rapid and intense onset, characterized by confusion and hysterical disassociation and rapid recovery. These psychoses may represent the impact of stress and minor organic disease on ss already brain damaged by numerous possible pathogenic features in the environment. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
