N2  - Reviews the book, Seelische Gesundheit (Mental Health) edited by W. Bettschart, H. Meng and E. Stern (see record 1960-05063-000). This very interesting book presents the opinions of continental European authorities on mental health. It is a collection of 32 papers written by Psychiatrists, Psychologists, educators, and a judge, a social worker, and a sculptor. The book is divided into several parts. First the working methods of mental hygiene, the ways of achieving its aims, and international problems are discussed. Papers on the mental health of marriage and the family follow. The greatest part of the book is dedicated to the problems of normal and disturbed childhood. The psychological needs of children, their reactions to environmental stimulation, the development of motivation and of conscience, the important--in modern society neglected--role of phantasy, epileptic and motor disorders, refugee children, and other subjects are discussed. Some papers give short case histories and illustrate the practical application of mental hygiene principles. Almost every paper is a little masterpiece of concise writing. The approach to the topics discussed is just as diversified as is the origin of the authors. This variegation does not distract the reader; the search for solutions of everyday problems is the integrating link. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
