T1  - Review of The African mind in health and disease: A study in ethnopsychiatry.
A1  - Speyer, Helen

Y1  - 1954//
N2  - Reviews the book, The African Mind in Health and Disease: A Study in Ethnopsychiatry by J. C. Carothers (1953). Those who are interested in problems of the epidemiology of mental illness and the impact of environmental and cultural influences on personality will want to read this book. Part I, which describes the physical background of the African, presents the anthropological data, factors of geography and climate, infectious diseases which must be taken into consideration. The section on cultural factors describes the important individual developmental stages, infancy, childhood, adolescence, etc., with emphasis on the elements which have significance for personality structure and growth. In Part II , problems of psychology and psychiatry are discussed, and comparisons are drawn to the American Negro as a displaced African, who may contribute to our understanding of the stability and extent of environmental, cultural elements in the determination of personality and mental functioning. In summarizing, the author concludes that rural Africans do not have the Europeans' clear-cut distinction between conscious and unconscious elements, and emotion may dominate the entire mind. The author suggests the possibility that many of the findings about the rural African may have general significance for other preliterate peoples. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
