T1  - Committee A--The family and parent education.
T2  - White House conference 1930: Addresses and abstracts of committee reports, White House conference on child health and protection called by President Hoover.
A1  - Stanley, Louise

Y1  - 1931//
N1  - White House Conference on Child Health and Protection. Nov, 1930. Washington. DC, US. This volume present the addresses and summary reports delivered at the conference.
N2  - The family is the most important agency in the health and protection of the child. It is probable that the most fundamental human values in family life are the product of the interaction of personalities within the family. The Committee has classified the functions of the family in four main categories: namely, control of environment, inculcation of social values, orientation, and liberation and recreation. The importance of some of these functions is self-evident--they are necessary for survival and while there is at present no scientific proof of the relative importance of the others, they are at least desirable, and a slighting of one would require compensation in some other aspect of family life. Social factors influencing family life include occupational status, race, nationality, geographic distribution and density of population. Other factors, including economics, also heavily influence family life. These factors, as well as housing and management of home activities, affect child development. The surest means of ensuring better child development and social adjustment is through parental education. In view of the responsibilities and obligations being laid upon the family as the primary agency for child health and protection, this Committee strongly recommends that various educational associations and organizations be requested to study the possibilities for organizing parent education as part of the systems of public instruction. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
