Y1  - 1963//
N2  - The classical view of schizophrenia with its subtypes opened the door to a consideration of a problem involving, roughly, half of our mental hospital populations. Then, brief historical background provided a setting for the examination of a variety of observations on children in an attempt to answer the question of childhood schizophrenia. Because of their close identification with schizophrenia, we next considered the nature of hallucinations in their natural setting and in their clinical-experimental study as they occurred in sensory deprivation studies and in drug-induced states. The benign stupors were analyzed in relation to their transient-permanent character. Then, organic and genetic or developmental theories of schizophrenia were weighed, and, in this connection, Searles' concepts of the nonhuman environment and of differentiation and integration were introduced and explained. A formulation of schizophrenia embodying these concepts was offered, defining it as essentially a failure of the individual to establish differentiated-integrated stimulus-response units or to maintain them after their establishment. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
