Y1  - 1949//
N2  - This chapter considers the inner life of the child. The personality of an individual emerges as a complex resultant of the interaction of his endowment with the experiences of living. The study of personality is thus concerned both with the self and the affective states and with the social relationships and traits which differentiate him from other members of a group. Personality is the whole child in action in a field of social forces. The personality of each individual child has a past, a present, and a future. The child carries his past with him, applies it to the present, and projects it into the future, where it undergoes further modification through the new experiences. The continuity of personality implies more than passive reaction to environment; it is a dynamic system which seeks and creates experience by selective awareness of surroundings. The stability of personality results in a strong resistance to displacement by temporary environmental variations. The school is one of the social groups to which a child refers his values, and schools share with the family and other associations the responsibility for shaping personality. Schools and teachers are instruments created by society for stabilizing, diffusing, and changing cultural values, as well as for maximizing individual personality and achievement. In this chapter, the following topics are discussed: bodily equilibrium and affect; the nervous system and emotion; characteristics of emotional states; psychosomatic relations; emotional maturity; fears and affective disturbances; group and individual frustration in the classroom; projective measurement methods; and mental health in the school program. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
