T1  - Common mechanisms of adjustment.
T2  - Basic problems of behavior.
A1  - Sherman, Mandel

A3  - Sherman, Mandel
Y1  - 1941//
N2  - Originally published in 1941, this chapter examines personality adjustment in light of what were--at the time--the current theories and empirical evidence. Although personality expression varies to a greater or lesser degree, according to the environmental conditions, it is usually possible to discover a consistent pattern, especially in adolescents and adults. It is therefore preferable to describe personality adjustment in terms of the consistent and persistent mechanisms of adjustment rather than in terms of given groups of desirable or undesirable traits. The author first discusses the most often observed of the various mechanisms of adjustment, including the compensatory method, the escape mechanism, and the defense mechanism. The chapter then focuses on aggressive behavior, discussing some of the factors involved in its development (including insecurity and frustration), type (including criticism, jealousy, and displaced aggression), and frequency. In the next section, the author discusses withdrawal behavior, usually considered to be the result of a type of frustration which does not involve the individual in aggressive retaliation. It is essentially a form of adjustment as the result of a fear of involvement in a situation from which the person anticipates undesirable consequences. The next topic of consideration is "phantasy", thought to be important because the knowledge of the contents of an individual's phantasies may be an important aid to a diagnosis of his personality. The chapter closes with a discussion of symbolic behavior, including the symbolism of language, symbolic thought, and symbolic activity which may function for the purpose of displacing emotional values from one object to another. Symbolic representation is also discussed in relation to neurotic behavior and schizophrenia, as a way of elucidating the nature of symbolic behavior in general. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
